Pied Flycatcher:  Small flycatchers, all in basic plumage, distinctive white patch on wing - some had brown throat well-demarcated from belly, some did not. Small white mark on side of wing that does not extend to teh end of the feather.  I've seen flocks here in previous Augusts, these stayed around a few days but seem to be petering out now.   At least one Spotted Flycatcher was in the flock (no white wing marks, fine streaking on flanks, patterned back).

photos.Locality: 千葉市--泉自然公園 (Chiba--Izumi Nature Park)

photos.Observation Details: Found by William Legge this morning.  Staked out for 1.5 hrs before refound.  On the shoreline, north side of lagoon in an area with some green algae wrack and grasses.  Hard to see, only came out for seconds at a time before retreating into deep marsh grass.  Seen well in flight twice with long tail with wel defined white outer rectices - very much like a White Wagtail in flight, though longer tail.  Head pattern is diffuse gray auriculars with gray extending to nape (no white crescent behind auricular patch as you would expect with an HY Citrine Wagtail.)  I do not know how to separate Eastern and Western Yellow Wagtail by sight.  Only gave off a few single pip calls in flight, no repeated song.

photos.Locality: Nunes Ridge - pasture above Nunes "A" Ranch
photos.Observation Details: Found by D. Mosur earlier in the day - I refound it in the American Pipit flock inside a cow pen.  Identified by call and sight.  Note white braces on back - unique to Red-throated and Pechora.  Face pattern (well-defined supercilium extending behind eye, broad sub-malar patch) and bill (gray at tip, buff-yellow at base) favor Red-throated.

Following reports from yesterday, went down to look for Grosbeaks.   The gates were locked on Saturday, but sure enough I could clearly see Evening Grosbeaks in the Chinese Pistache trees in the parking lot, feeding.   Took lots of photographs through locked gate at a distance of about 50 feet - seemed mostly female.  After about 12 minutes the Palo Alto police showed up with lights blaring (man with 700mm lens photographing HP headquarters?).   They were exceedingly polite when I showed them photos of the birds.  No problem.
Really unexpected.  Almost the only bird I saw all afternoon.
